Package au.csiro.pathling.fhirpath

Interface Numeric

  • All Known Implementing Classes:
    DecimalLiteralPath, DecimalPath, IntegerLiteralPath, IntegerPath, QuantityLiteralPath, QuantityPath
    public interface Numeric
    Describes a path that represents a numeric value, and can be the subject of math operations.
    Author:
    John Grimes

    • Method Detail

      • getMathOperation

        @Nonnull
Function<Numeric,​NonLiteralPath> getMathOperation​(@Nonnull
                                                        Numeric.MathOperation operation,
                                                        @Nonnull
                                                        String expression,
                                                        @Nonnull
                                                        Dataset<Row> dataset)
        Get a function that can take two Numeric paths and return a NonLiteralPath that contains the result of a math operation. The type of operation is controlled by supplying a Numeric.MathOperation.
        Parameters:
        operation - The Numeric.MathOperation type to retrieve a result for
        expression - The FHIRPath expression to use within the result
        dataset - The Dataset to use within the result
        Returns:
        A Function that takes a Numeric as its parameter, and returns a NonLiteralPath.

      • getNumericValueColumn

        @Nonnull
Column getNumericValueColumn()
        Returns:
        a Column that provides a value that can me used in math operations

      • getNumericContextColumn

        @Nonnull
Column getNumericContextColumn()
        Provides a Column that provides additional context that informs the way that math operations are carried out. This is used for Quantity math, so that the operation function has access to the canonicalized units.
        Returns:
        a Column that provides additional context for math operations

      • getFhirType

        @Nonnull
Enumerations.FHIRDefinedType getFhirType()
        The FHIR data type of the element being represented by this expression.

        Note that there can be multiple valid FHIR types for a given FHIRPath type, e.g. uri and code both map to the String FHIRPath type.

        Returns:
        the FHIR data type of the expression
        See Also:
        Using FHIR types in expressions
